Problem 1: Storing Your Work and R Commands (10 points)

Code Blocks:

When you open a new R Markdown file, you should see a block of code (beginning with three grave accent marks – similar to apostrophes, but located next to the 1 key on a standard keyboard – then an {r}, then three more accent marks). This block should have a light gray background color in R Studio. This is a code block! You can type commands into this block, and they will be executed by R and included in your output.

Let’s test out the following command:

# By the way, my hometown is Louisville, KY
print("Hello, World! My name is Zach Branson.")
## [1] "Hello, World! My name is Zach Branson."

Change the above code so that it outputs the following text: “Hello, World! My name is [your name].”

Code Comments:

Comments should be used frequently when writing code to give insight into what each piece of code is doing. To add a comment to your code, start a new line with the # symbol.

Change the existing comment in your first code block so that it says, “By the way, my hometown is [your hometown].”

Notice that the text in the comments shows up in the code block in the output file, but not in the actual output when you click “Knit HTML”. Comments exist to help you and others who read your code. Note that, within 36-315, “others” in the previous sentence are graders. You should add code to your comments so 36-315 graders understand what you are trying to achieve in your code, even if you make a mistake. If you don’t leave comments in your code, partial credit is less likely.

Problem 3: Accessing Libraries, Datasets, and Variables (20 points)

In R, there are many libraries or packages/groups of programs that are not permanently stored in R, so we have to load them when we want to use them. You can load an R library by typing library(libraryName). (Sometimes we need to download the library first, as described in Lab0.)

There are many functions that are only available after you load a library. Throughout 36-315, please remember to load libraries by including library(libraryName) within a code block in an .Rmd file to load the functions you need; otherwise, you’ll get an error saying that the function is undefined. For example, the following code chunk loads the datasets library:

library(datasets)

This loads many datasets in R; we’ll consider one of them, called trees.

Looking at the help documentation for the trees dataset, the names of the three variables in the trees dataset are: Girth, Height, and Volume. There are 31 observations in the dataset.

  1. (10pts) To access a particular variable within a dataset, you use the dollar sign format: datasetName$variableName. For example, the following code displays the Girth variable within the trees dataset, as well as its mean:
#girth variable
trees$Girth
##  [1]  8.3  8.6  8.8 10.5 10.7 10.8 11.0 11.0 11.1 11.2 11.3 11.4 11.4 11.7 12.0
## [16] 12.9 12.9 13.3 13.7 13.8 14.0 14.2 14.5 16.0 16.3 17.3 17.5 17.9 18.0 18.0
## [31] 20.6
#mean of girth variable

What is the 50% quantile and standard deviation for each of the three variables in the trees dataset? (Be sure to include R code that allows you to answer this question.) Hint: Problem 2 should have helped you figure out what functions you need for this part.

Here’s the code to compute the 50% quantile and standard deviation of the three variables in the trees dataset:

#50% quantiles (aka the median)
quantile(trees$Girth, probs = 0.5)
##  50% 
## 12.9
quantile(trees$Height, probs = 0.5)
## 50% 
##  76
quantile(trees$Volume, probs = 0.5)
##  50% 
## 24.2
#standard deviation
sd(trees$Girth)
## [1] 3.138139
sd(trees$Height)
## [1] 6.371813
sd(trees$Volume)
## [1] 16.43785

We see that the 50% quantile for Girth, Height, and Volume are 12.9, 76, and 24.2, respectively. Meanwhile, the standard deviation for Girth, Height, and Volume are 3.14, 6.37, 16.44, respectively. (Also, note that the 50% quantile is the same as the median.)

  1. (10pts) Now we’ll use the ggplot() function to create a bar plot of the river variable. The river variable is either “A” (for Allegheny), “M” (for Monongahela), or “O” (for Ohio). To make things easier, we provide the code for you to do this below; just uncomment the code and Knit your .Rmd file accordingly to create the bar plot. Note that the code will not run unless you’ve loaded the tidyverse library in your .Rmd file! In what follows, you must answer some questions about the code and plot.
# Create the bar plot
ggplot(bridges, aes(x = river)) + 
 geom_bar(fill = "darkblue") + 
 labs(
 title = "Number of Bridges in Pittsburgh by River",
 subtitle = "A = Allegheny River, M = Monongahela River, O = Ohio River",
 x = "River",
 y = "Number of Bridges",
 caption = "Source: Pittsburgh Bridges Dataset"
 )

Answer the following questions about the code and plot:

  • In general, ggplot() code takes the following format: ggplot(blank1, aes(x = blank2)). Looking at the above code, what kind of R object should blank1 be, and what should blank2 be?

blank1 should be the dataset that you want to plot, and blank2 should be the variable within that dataset you want to plot.

  • What do you think the line geom_bar(fill = "darkblue") does?

It creates a bar plot where the bars are dark blue.

  • What do you think the remaining lines of code do (contained in labs())?

It creates “labels” for the plot - specifically, a title, subtitle, caption, and x-axis and y-axis labels.

Note that, unlike the code we saw in Problem 3, the dollar sign notation isn’t needed within ggplot().

# PUT YOUR ROSE DIAGRAM CODE HERE
ggplot(bridges, aes(x = river)) + 
 geom_bar(fill = "darkblue") + coord_polar() + scale_y_sqrt() +
 labs(
 title = "Number of Bridges in Pittsburgh by River",
 subtitle = "A = Allegheny River, M = Monongahela River, O = Ohio River",
 x = "River",
 y = "Number of Bridges",
 caption = "Source: Pittsburgh Bridges Dataset"
 )

The code scale_y_sqrt() makes it such that the radius of each “petal” is proportional to the square-root of the number of bridges in each category (instead of proportional to the number itself). This ensures that the area of each “petal” is proportional to the number of observations in each category, rather than the square of the number (as discussed in class).

  1. (5pts) Sometimes datasets don’t have every variable you want to visualize, in which case you have to create new columns in your data. Now we’ll use the mutate() function to create two new columns in the bridges dataset:
  • over_allegheny: indicates whether the bridge crosses the Allegheny River ("yes" or "no")
  • length_binary: indicates whether the bridge is at least 1000 feet long ("long" or "short")

Here’s some “template code” you can use to create these columns:

# Create the new variables
bridges <- mutate(bridges, 
   over_allegheny = ifelse(river ==  "A", "yes" , "no" ),
   length_binary = ifelse(length <  1000, "short" , "long" ))

Note that the mutate() function is within the tidyverse library; so, remember that the above code runs only because you’ve already loaded the tidyverse library earlier in this .Rmd file.

  1. (10pts) The most common kind of summary statistic for a categorical variable is the counts of each category, often displayed as a contingency table (also known as a frequency table). To make a contingency table in R, you use the table() function. The following code should display a contingency table for the length_binary variable (after you’ve completed Part E):
table(bridges$length_binary)
## 
##  long short 
##    61    11

Uncomment and run the above code and make sure a contingency table displays. Are there more "long" bridges or "short" bridges?

As we can see, there are many more long bridges than short bridges.

It can also be helpful to create a table of proportions, instead of a table of counts. Write a line of code that displays a table of proportions for the bridges$length_binary variable. In other words, your table should display the proportion of “short” and “long” bridges. To do this, you can either use the prop.table() function or the table() function (appropriately divided by a number).

Here are two ways you could display the table of percentages:

#using prop.table() and table() together:
prop.table(table(bridges$length_binary))
## 
##      long     short 
## 0.8472222 0.1527778
#using just table():
table(bridges$length_binary)/nrow(bridges)
## 
##      long     short 
## 0.8472222 0.1527778
